# Fluff Date: 2026-02-18 17:17:24
overview:<p>The Pulverizer is a 90-ton assault BattleMech introduced in 2823 as the signature command platform of Clan Wolverine. Following the successes of lighter evolutionary designs like the Mercury II and Stag, Khan Sarah McEvedy called for a completely new BattleMech tailored to the overwhelming firepower her warriors demanded. The resulting design married Star League-era construction technology with enhanced prototype weapons, creating a chassis defined by extreme durability and long-range striking power.</p><p>After the Wolverine Annihilation, Clan Snow Raven recognized the design's merits and began manufacturing the Pulverizer at Industrial Complex Raven Alpha on Lum in 2824. Despite enduring decades of controversy and Grand Council censure over its tainted origins, the Snow Ravens operated the Pulverizer throughout the Golden Century until the rise of the OmniMech rendered the design obsolete. Snow Raven scientists ultimately preserved the Pulverizer's legacy by using it as the foundation for the Kingfisher assault OmniMech.</p>

capabilities:<p>Built as a command platform, the Pulverizer prioritizes long-range engagement and survivability over speed. At 90 tons, the design moves at a modest 64 km/h on a standard fusion engine, relying on weapons reach and thick protection rather than maneuverability. Over fifteen tons of ferro-fibrous armor combined with CASE protection and the standard engine make the Pulverizer extraordinarily difficult to destroy, a trait that proved decisive in early Clan Trials where opponents often fell long before the Pulverizer sustained critical damage.</p><p>The weapons suite centers on a Shredder-II Enhanced ER PPC, a transitional weapon more powerful than standard Star League particle projectors but lacking the devastating output of later Clan-standard ER PPCs. Twin large lasers provide secondary firepower at closer ranges, while a Type III "Great Bow" LRM-10 rack adds sustained indirect fire capability. A Guardian ECM Suite disrupts enemy targeting and sensor networks, reinforcing the Pulverizer's role as a command platform.</p><p>The use of Star League-era endo steel construction saves critical weight, enabling the heavy armor and weapons loadout without sacrificing structural integrity. Fifteen double heat sinks manage the considerable heat output adequately, though sustained alpha strikes can push the design's thermal limits.</p>

deployment:<p>The fully upgraded Pulverizer represents Clan Snow Raven's effort to modernize the design with contemporary Clan technology around 2845. The weapons suite is completely reworked around a Clan ER PPC and twin large pulse lasers, replacing the transitional-era Enhanced ER PPC and standard large lasers of earlier variants with proven Clan-standard systems. An LRM-10 launcher provides continued missile support, while an ECM Suite maintains the 'Mech's electronic warfare capability. Eighteen double heat sinks manage the updated weapons load effectively. This variant represented the Snow Ravens' final effort to extract maximum capability from the Pulverizer chassis before transitioning to the Kingfisher OmniMech program.</p>

history:<p>The Pulverizer's history is inseparable from the tragic fate of Clan Wolverine. Following Operation KLONDIKE, Khan Sarah McEvedy recognized that mere refits of SLDF designs could not sustain her Clan's ambitions. While the Mercury II and Stag had already pushed beyond simple Star League re-engineering, the Pulverizer represented a fundamentally new design philosophy, a purpose-built command 'Mech tailored to Wolverine doctrine. Introduced in 2823, the Pulverizer entered service just as tensions between the Wolverines and the rest of the Clans reached their breaking point.</p><p>The design saw its first major combat during the Trials leading to the Wolverine Annihilation and throughout Operation SWITCHBACK, the coordinated campaign that destroyed Clan Wolverine. Wolverine saKhan Franklin Hallis reportedly piloted a Pulverizer during the final stand at Barbados. Ironically, the design's effectiveness during these engagements caught the attention of Clan Snow Raven, who salvaged Pulverizers and began their own production at Industrial Complex Raven Alpha on Lum in 2824.</p><p>The Snow Ravens' continued use of a design created by the Not-Named Clan proved deeply controversial throughout the Golden Century. The Grand Council entertained numerous censure motions against the Ravens, and rival Clans (particularly the Ghost Bears) treated victories achieved with Pulverizers as dishonorable. A notable engagement on Brim in 2835 saw a Snow Raven officer use his Pulverizer to devastating effect against a Ghost Bear garrison defending an Eagle factory, destroying a Shogun in brutal close-quarters fighting. The Ghost Bears petitioned the Grand Council, insisting that the use of dezgra BattleMechs could only produce dezgra MechWarriors. The Council ruled against the Bears, but the stigma surrounding the Pulverizer never fully dissipated.</p><p>The rise of the OmniMech ultimately ended active Pulverizer production. Rather than discard the design entirely, Snow Raven scientists used the proven chassis as the foundation for the Kingfisher, an assault OmniMech that debuted in 2887 and carried forward the Pulverizer's emphasis on durability while shedding the tainted Wolverine association.</p><p>Though out of production for centuries, a handful of Pulverizers survived in Snow Raven stores. During the Dark Age, several of these venerable machines reappeared in Raven Alliance formations operating along the Federated Suns border, their mere presence sufficient to alarm militia units unfamiliar with the rare design. Persistent but unverified reports from intelligence sources within the reunified Free Worlds League also claimed sightings of a single iridescent green Pulverizer attacking worlds with Interstellar Expeditions presence near the Periphery border, though such claims remain dubious at best.</p>

